## How to Run

1. Upload the competition dataset to Kaggle
2. Update `DATA_ROOT` path in Cell 1
3. Select GPU accelerator (T4 or H100) — `tree_method='hist'` works on CPU, switch to `'gpu_hist'` for GPU
4. Run all cells sequentially

**Runtime:** ~20–40 min depending on accelerator

**Dependencies:**
```
catboost, lightgbm, xgboost, scikit-learn, category_encoders, pandas, numpy, matplotlib, seaborn, tqdm, joblib
```

---

## Tech Stack

- **ML Frameworks:** LightGBM, XGBoost, Scikit-learn
- **Encoding:** category_encoders (Target Encoding with smoothing)
- **Infrastructure:** Kaggle Notebooks
- **Language:** Python 3.10+

---

## Methodology Summary

A 3-class churn classifier built on an OOT-safe architecture that eliminates calendar-based features in favor of relative time-since-subscription signals. Feature engineering spans 6 data tables with emphasis on payment friction detection (3DS friction, geo-mismatch, failure taxonomy), cold-start behavioral metrics (time-to-first-success, failed-before-success), and engagement velocity (credit burn rate, NSFW intensity, weekly activity trends). Financial features are normalized via plan-relative Price Ratios to guard against pricing changes. The 5.5 GB generation log is processed through chunked reading with Parquet caching. High-cardinality categoricals (bank name, country) use smoothed Target Encoding fitted strictly within CV folds. The final model is a soft-voting ensemble of LightGBM and XGBoost, validated on Stratified 5-Fold CV without artificial class balancing, achieving 0.61 accuracy and 0.5232 weighted F1 on the three-class problem.
